Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Line a #baking sheet{} with @aluminum foil{}. Quarter @Yukon Gold Potatoes{12%ounce}, then place on lined sheet. Toss with a large drizzle of @olive oil{∞}, @Herbes de Provence{1/2%tsp} (we'll use the rest later), @salt{∞}, and @pepper{∞}. Roast in oven until crisp, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop @garlic{2%clove}. Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add garlic and cook, stirring, until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}.

Add @Spinach{5%ounce} to pot and cook until just wilted, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add @Flour{1%tablespoon} and @Milk{1/3%cup} and stir well. Season with @salt{∞} and @pepper{∞}. Bring to a simmer and let bubble, stirring occasionally, until thick, about ~{2%minutes}. Stir in @Parmesan Cheese{1/4%cup} and @Monterey Jack Cheese{1/4%cup}. Continue simmering until creamy and thick, about ~{2%minutes}. Season with @salt{∞} and @pepper{∞}. Keep covered off heat.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{∞} in a #medium pan{} over medium-high heat. Pat @New York Strip Steak{12%ounce} dry with a #paper towel{}. Season all over with @salt{∞}, @pepper{∞}, and remaining @Herbes de Provence{1/2%tsp}. Cook in pan until nicely browned on bottom, ~{6-7%minutes}, then flip and cook on other side to desired doneness, ~{5-6%minutes} more. Transfer to a #cutting board{} and let rest.

While steak cooks, peel, halve, and thinly slice @Shallot{1}. Pick @Parsley{1/4%ounce} leaves and roughly chop; discard stems. Once steak is done, add a drizzle of @olive oil{1/4%teaspoon} to same pan over medium-high heat. Add shallot and cook until just softened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Reduce heat to medium-low and stir in @Beef Demi-Glace{1}, @Balsamic Glaze{1%tablespoon} (we sent more), and @water{2%tablespoon}. Season with @salt{∞} and @pepper{∞}.

Bring sauce to a simmer, then reduce heat to low. Add half the parsley and @Butter{1%tablespoon}, stirring to melt. Add up to @?water{1%tablespoon} more if sauce is stiff. Slice steak. Divide between plates along with potatoes and spinach (you may want to reheat it). Drizzle with sauce and garnish with remaining parsley.

> "Meat and potatoes" gets elevated when you add a sophisticated sauce. Here, that's a mix of balsamic glaze and demi-glace, which bring tart and savory flavors with a little sweetness to round it out. The sauce is drizzled onto our New York strip steak, providing a bright contrast to the richness of the beef. With creamed spinach and herb-roasted spuds on the side, everything about this dish says classic comforts done right.